Data Wrangling and Analysis in R

1. Installing packages

In R, packages are a collection of functions that provide functinalities not given by the R core functionalities. Well install tidyverse packages which will provide us with packages for performing data manipulation and analysis.

Lets install tidyverse packages in Rstudio

Load tidyverse for use in our notebook

library(tidyverse)

2. Load dataset

MTN Telecom offers mobile and internet services to its customers. These services include phone, multiple lines, internet, online security, online backup, device protection, tech support, and streaming TV and movies.

You have been provided with the current customer data. Since you will be working towards a descriptive report than a predictive one, you decide to think critically of the kind of questions that would help you craft customer retention programs. You then later use the given data set to answer your questions but before you start, you reading, explore, clean and visualise your dataset.

# Import, Load dataset and preview its summarized information.

MTN_df <- read.csv("https://bit.ly/2ZlpzjF")
head(MTN_df)
#check the no of rows and cols
dim(MTN_df)
## [1] 7050   21

3. Data cleaning

Data understanding

# Step1: get column names and perform standardisation
names(MTN_df)
##  [1] "customerID"       "GENDER"           "SeniorCitizen"    "PARTNER"         
##  [5] "Dependents"       "tenure"           "PhoneService"     "MultipleLines"   
##  [9] "InternetService"  "OnlineSecurity"   "OnlineBackup"     "DeviceProtection"
## [13] "TECHSUPPORT"      "StreamingTV"      "StreamingMovies"  "Contract"        
## [17] "PaperlessBilling" "PaymentMethod"    "MonthlyCharges"   "TotalCharges"    
## [21] "Churn"
#Step 2: convert all column names to lower case
names(MTN_df) <- tolower(names(MTN_df))
names(MTN_df)
##  [1] "customerid"       "gender"           "seniorcitizen"    "partner"         
##  [5] "dependents"       "tenure"           "phoneservice"     "multiplelines"   
##  [9] "internetservice"  "onlinesecurity"   "onlinebackup"     "deviceprotection"
## [13] "techsupport"      "streamingtv"      "streamingmovies"  "contract"        
## [17] "paperlessbilling" "paymentmethod"    "monthlycharges"   "totalcharges"    
## [21] "churn"
#Step3: Remove all leading and trailing spaces
names(MTN_df) <- trimws(names(MTN_df), which = c("both"))
names(MTN_df)
##  [1] "customerid"       "gender"           "seniorcitizen"    "partner"

Removing Irrelevant data

#check for duplicates
MTN_df[duplicated(MTN_df), ]
#remove duplicates from the dataframe
MTN_df <- unique(MTN_df)

#confirm all duplicates are removed
MTN_df[duplicated(MTN_df), ]

handle missing data

#check if there is missing data from the df
colSums(is.na(MTN_df))
##       customerid           gender    seniorcitizen          partner 
##                0                0                3                0 
##       dependents           tenure     phoneservice    multiplelines 
##                0               11                0                0 
##  internetservice   onlinesecurity     onlinebackup deviceprotection 
##                0                0                0                0 
##      techsupport      streamingtv  streamingmovies         contract 
##                0                0                0                0 
## paperlessbilling    paymentmethod   monthlycharges     totalcharges 
##                0                0               12               23 
##            churn 
##                0
#Remove all records with missing data
clean_df <- na.omit(MTN_df)

#confirm no missing values
colSums(is.na(clean_df))
##       customerid           gender    seniorcitizen          partner 
##                0                0                0                0 
##       dependents           tenure     phoneservice    multiplelines 
##                0                0                0                0 
##  internetservice   onlinesecurity     onlinebackup deviceprotection 
##                0                0                0                0 
##      techsupport      streamingtv  streamingmovies         contract 
##                0                0                0                0 
## paperlessbilling    paymentmethod   monthlycharges     totalcharges 
##                0                0                0                0 
##            churn 
##                0
unique(clean_df$seniorcitizen)
## [1] 0 1
# column senior_citizen should be a boolean
clean_df$seniorcitizen[clean_df$seniorcitizen == 0] <- 'No'
clean_df$seniorcitizen[clean_df$seniorcitizen == 1] <- 'Yes'

#Check unique values
unique(clean_df$seniorcitizen)
## [1] "No"  "Yes"
#resolving the issues in the 'paymentmethod' variable

# - Replace 'Mailed checkkk' with 'Mailed check',
clean_df$paymentmethod[clean_df$paymentmethod == "Mailed checkkk"] <- "Mailed check"

# - Replace 'Electronic checkk', 'Electronic check'
clean_df$paymentmethod[clean_df$paymentmethod == "Electronic checkk"] <- "Electronic check"

#confirm all replacements have been done
unique(clean_df$paymentmethod)
## [1] "Electronic check"          "Mailed check"             
## [3] "Bank transfer (automatic)" "Credit card (automatic)"
# visual distribution of the outliers using a box plot

#prepare data
tenure <- clean_df$tenure
monthly_charge <- clean_df$monthlycharges
Total_charge <- clean_df$totalcharges


#plot the chart
boxplot(tenure,
        names = "tenure",
        xlab = "Customers",
        ylab = "Tenure", 
        main = "boxplot with customer tenure")

boxplot(monthly_charge,
        names = "monthly",
        xlab = "Customers",
        ylab = "Billed Amount", 
        main = "boxplot with monthly charging data")

boxplot(Total_charge,
        names = "Total",
        xlab = "Customers",
        ylab = "Billed Amount", 
        main = "boxplot with Total charging data")

Dealing with outliers

#Removing the outliers using IQR method
dim(clean_df)
## [1] 7015   21
#calculate lower and upper percentiles
lower_bound <- quantile(clean_df$tenure, 0.025)
upper_bound <- quantile(clean_df$tenure, 0.975)
lower_bound
## 2.5% 
##    1
upper_bound
## 97.5% 
##    72
#getting values that are not outliers
tenure_not_outlier_values <- which(clean_df$tenure > lower_bound & clean_df$tenure < upper_bound)

IQR_df<- clean_df[tenure_not_outlier_values,]

dim(IQR_df)
## [1] 6035   21
lower_bound <- quantile(IQR_df$monthlycharges, 0.025)
upper_bound <- quantile(IQR_df$monthlycharges, 0.975)
lower_bound
##  2.5% 
## 19.45
upper_bound
## 97.5% 
##   110
#getting values that are not outliers
not_outlier_values <- which(IQR_df$monthlycharges > lower_bound & IQR_df$monthlycharges < upper_bound)

IQR2_df<- IQR_df[not_outlier_values, ]

#check values after removing outliers
dim(IQR2_df)
## [1] 5710   21
lower_bound <- quantile(IQR2_df$totalcharges, 0.025)
upper_bound <- quantile(IQR2_df$totalcharges, 0.975)
lower_bound
##  2.5% 
## 90.05
upper_bound
##    97.5% 
## 6856.587
#getting values that are not outliers
not_outlier_values <- which(IQR2_df$totalcharges > lower_bound & IQR2_df$monthlycharges < upper_bound)

Telecom_clean_df<- IQR2_df[not_outlier_values, ]

#check the new df
dim(Telecom_clean_df)
## [1] 5566   21

4. Data analysis

Since our research question requires us to focus on how we can retain customers, the main variable to work with is the churn variable.

Research specific analysis

What percentage of customers from our dataset churned?

# plotting a pie chart to investigate whether MTN customers churned

# prepare data
df <- Telecom_clean_df %>% 
  group_by(churn) %>% # Variable to be transformed
  count() %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  mutate(perc = `n` / sum(`n`)) %>% 
  arrange(perc) %>%
  mutate(labels = scales::percent(perc))

# df_1 <- Telecom_clean_df %>%
#   count(churn)
# df_1

#Plot
ggplot(df, aes(x = "", y = perc, fill = churn)) +
  geom_col() +
  geom_text(aes(label = labels),
            position = position_stack(vjust = 0.5)) +
  labs(
    fill = "Churn", 
    title = "Churn Distribution"
  ) +
  coord_polar(theta = "y")+ 
  theme_void()

Summary of Findings

Based on the results of the analysis, the following conclusions were arrived at:

There is no significant difference in churn rate between male and female subscribers. So this is not an area management needs to worry about. Majority of the customers are not senior citizens so this makes this dataset biased and hard to identify whether being a senior citizen affects churn rate. Not having a partner increases the likelihood of churning. Not having dependents increases the likelihood of churning. theres no significant difference between customers with multiple lines and those that do not. Customers on a month to month contract have a higher propensity to churn compared to those with long term contract

Recommendations

In order to create an effective customer retention program, management should take the following measures:

Focus more on meeting the needs of non-senior citizens. Focus more on having customers that have partners and/or dependents since these people are less likely to churn. Alternatively, management can come up with services specifically designed for customers without parters and/or dependents. This would require additional research. Focus more on getting customers to long term contract
